# pulsar-rs: Future-based Rust client for [Apache Pulsar](https://pulsar.apache.org/)
[![crates](https://img.shields.io/crates/v/pulsar.svg)](https://crates.io/crates/pulsar) [![docs](https://img.shields.io/docsrs/pulsar)](https://docs.rs/pulsar)
This is a pure Rust client for Apache Pulsar that does not depend on the C++ Pulsar library. It provides an async/await based API, compatible with [Tokio](https://tokio.rs/) and [async-std](https://async.rs/).
Features:
  * URL based (``pulsar`:```//```` and ``pulsar`+`ssl`:```//````) connections with DNS lookup;
  * Multi topic consumers (based on a regex or list);
  * TLS connection;
  * Configurable executor (Tokio or async-std);
  * Automatic reconnection with exponential back off;
  * Message batching;
  * Compression with LZ4, zlib, zstd or Snappy (can be deactivated with Cargo features);
  * Telemetry using [tracing](https://github.com/tokio-rs/tracing) crate (can be activated with Cargo features).


## Getting Started
Add the following dependencies in your ``Cargo.toml``:
```
`futures = "0.3"
pulsar = "5.1"
tokio = "1.0"
`
```

Try out [examples](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/examples):
  * [producer](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/examples/producer.rs)
  * [consumer](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/examples/consumer.rs)
  * [reader](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/examples/reader.rs)

See [LICENSE-APACHE](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/LICENSE-APACHE), [LICENSE-MIT](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/LICENSE-MIT), and [COPYRIGHT](https://github.com/streamnative/pulsar-rs/blob/78983a4006c4f06e2c9e8619a7c94ec7f067a9b0/COPYRIGHT) for details.

Founded in 2019 by the original creators of Apache Pulsar, [StreamNative](https://streamnative.io/) is one of the leading contributors to the open-source Apache Pulsar project. advisory.title: Use-After-Free in `Md::fetch` and `Cipher::fetch`
advisory.description:
When a `Some(...)` value was passed to the `properties` argument of either of these functions, a use-after-free would result.

In practice this would nearly always result in OpenSSL treating the properties as an empty string (due to `CString::drop`'s behavior).

The maintainers thank [quitbug](https://github.com/quitbug/) for reporting this vulnerability to us.

advisory.title: Some AES functions may panic when overflow checking is enabled.
advisory.description:
`ring::aead::quic::HeaderProtectionKey::new_mask()` may panic when overflow
checking is enabled. In the QUIC protocol, an attacker can induce this panic by
sending a specially-crafted packet. Even unintentionally it is likely to occur
in 1 out of every 2**32 packets sent and/or received.

On 64-bit targets operations using `ring::aead::{AES_128_GCM, AES_256_GCM}` may
panic when overflow checking is enabled, when encrypting/decrypting approximately
68,719,476,700 bytes (about 64 gigabytes) of data in a single chunk. Protocols
like TLS and SSH are not affected by this because those protocols break large
amounts of data into small chunks. Similarly, most applications will not
attempt to encrypt/decrypt 64GB of data in one chunk.

Overflow checking is not enabled in release mode by default, but
`RUSTFLAGS="-C overflow-checks"` or `overflow-checks = true` in the Cargo.toml
profile can override this. Overflow checking is usually enabled by default in
debug mode.

advisory.title: Marvin Attack: potential key recovery through timing sidechannels
advisory.description:
### Impact
Due to a non-constant-time implementation, information about the private key is leaked through timing information which is observable over the network. An attacker may be able to use that information to recover the key.

### Patches
No patch is yet available, however work is underway to migrate to a fully constant-time implementation.

### Workarounds
The only currently available workaround is to avoid using the `rsa` crate in settings where attackers are able to observe timing information, e.g. local use on a non-compromised computer is fine.

### References
This vulnerability was discovered as part of the "[Marvin Attack]", which revealed several implementations of RSA including OpenSSL had not properly mitigated timing sidechannel attacks.

[Marvin Attack]: https://people.redhat.com/~hkario/marvin/

advisory.title: paste - no longer maintained
advisory.description:
The creator of the crate `paste` has stated in the [`README.md`](https://github.com/dtolnay/paste/blob/master/README.md) 
that this project is not longer maintained as well as archived the repository

advisory.title: Broadcast channel calls clone in parallel, but does not require `Sync`
advisory.description:
The broadcast channel internally calls `clone` on the stored value when
receiving it, and only requires `T:Send`. This means that using the broadcast
channel with values that are `Send` but not `Sync` can trigger unsoundness if
the `clone` implementation makes use of the value being `!Sync`.

Thank you to Austin Bonander for finding and reporting this issue.

enriched_crate.readme_summary: The `pulsar` crate is a pure Rust asynchronous client for Apache Pulsar, offering an `async/await` API compatible with both Tokio and async-std. It supports features like URL-based connections, TLS, multi-topic consumers via regex, automatic reconnection with exponential backoff, message batching, and compression (LZ4, zlib, zstd, Snappy). Designed for high-performance messaging, it enables seamless message production and consumption with configurable executors and serialization/deserialization support.
enriched_crate.factual_counterfactual:
### Pair 1: Async/Await API and Compatibility  
✅ Factual: The `pulsar` crate provides a pure Rust async/await API for interacting with Apache Pulsar, and it is compatible with both `Tokio` and `async-std` executors.  
❌ Counterfactual: The `pulsar` crate requires the Apache Pulsar C++ library to function and does not support `async-std`.  

---

### Pair 2: Message Compression  
✅ Factual: The `pulsar` crate supports message compression using LZ4, zlib, zstd, or Snappy, and these can be disabled via Cargo features.  
❌ Counterfactual: The `pulsar` crate only supports LZ4 compression and does not allow disabling compression through Cargo features.  

---

### Pair 3: Multi-topic Consumers  
✅ Factual: The `pulsar` crate allows multi-topic consumers to subscribe to topics based on a regular expression.  
❌ Counterfactual: The `pulsar` crate only supports single-topic consumers and does not provide regex-based topic subscriptions.
